== Keywords ==

Braces, double brackets and exclamation mark are keywords. That means in order to use them correctly you need spaces around them!


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="16">

<source lang="bash"># Bash keywords
type if then elif else fi time for in until while do done case esac coproc select function { } [[ ]] !</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>if is a shell keyword
then is a shell keyword
elif is a shell keyword

fi is a shell keyword

for is a shell keyword

until is a shell keyword
while is a shell keyword
do is a shell keyword
done is a shell keyword
case is a shell keyword
esac is a shell keyword
coproc is a shell keyword
select is a shell keyword
function is a shell keyword
{ is a shell keyword
} is a shell keyword
[[ is a shell keyword
]] is a shell keyword
! is a shell keyword
</pre>

</div>

</pre>

<div class="cell markdown">

= Functions =

# Functions in Bash are not functions like in other languages. They are actually <code>commands</code>. Functions are used as if they were command line binaries or scripts.
# Shell commands are connected by <code>pipes</code> (aka streams), and not by fundamental or user-defined data types as in ''real'' programming languages. There is <code>no such thing as a return value</code> for a command. (Although there is a return statement - see below.)
# When a function wants to get input it reads it from its input stream, or the argument list. In both cases text strings have to be parsed. The shell with its pipe-based architecture is <code>purely string-based</code>!
# When a command wants to return something it has to <code>echo/printf</code> it to its output stream.
# The caller can use command substitution <code>$()</code> to capture the output.
# Another practiced way is to store the return values in dedicated, <code>global variables</code>. Writing to the output stream is clearer and more flexible, because it can also take binary data, though.
# Think of the <code>exit code</code> as a bonus that other languages don't have, or as a <code>Schmutzeffekt</code> of shell functions. The meaning of the exit code is up to the shell programmer!
# Often by convention an exit status of <code>0 means success</code>, <code>1-255 means failure</code> and the exit code can be regarded as a failure number.
# Just to make sure: <code>return/exit</code> can only take a value from 0-255. Values other than 0 are <code>not necessarily errors</code>. There is always an <code>exit status</code>.
# The <code>argument list</code> is only for <code>decoration</code> and you never put anything inside them.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

== How to define functions ==

There are two ways to define functions.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== 1. With the <code>function</code> keyword ===

a) The <code>argument list</code> is <code>optional</code>.<br>

b) <code>Coding style</code>: Do not use an argument list.


</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">function success {
    echo "I am successful!"
    return 0
}</source>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== 2. Without the <code>function</code> keyword ===

The <code>argument list</code> is <code>mandatory</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">success() {
    echo "I am successful!"
    return 0
}</source>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Passing and Accessing Arguments ===

Use <code>$1</code>, <code>$2</code>, <code>$3</code>, ..., <code>$9</code>, <code>${10}</code>, <code>${11}</code>, ... to catch the parameters.


</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">function printme {
    echo "You gave me $# argument(s)!"
    echo -n $1
}</source>

</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">printme</source>

</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">printme 'Hello'</source>

</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">printme 'Hello' 'World'</source>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Returning Values ===


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== 1. echo/printf values to the output stream ====


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="21">

<source lang="bash">function add {
    # $((...)) to calculate mathematical expressions
    sum=$(( $1 + $2 ))
    echo $sum
}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="22">

<source lang="bash">add 1 2</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>3[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== 1. Capture Return Values via Command Substition Using <code>$()</code> ====


</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">result=$(add 1 2)
echo $result</source>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== 2. Use Global Variables to Provide Return Values ====

The <code>sum</code> variable in our add function is actually a <code>global variable</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="23">

<source lang="bash">echo $sum</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>3[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Variable Scope ===

Using <code>local variables</code> in order to not pollute the <code>global namespace</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">function add_local {
    local sum=$(($1+$2))
    echo -n $sum
}</source>

</div>
<div class="cell code">

<source lang="bash">add_local 5 6</source>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

The global variable from above did not change.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="24">

<source lang="bash">echo $sum</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>3[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== 3. Argument References ====

As of Bash 4.3+, we can pass an input argument by reference using <code>declare -n 'reference'</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="25">

<source lang="bash">function add_by_ref {
    declare -n add_ref=$3
    add_ref=$(( $1 + $2 )) 
}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="29">

<source lang="bash">add_by_ref 4 5 myAddRefResult</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="30">

<source lang="bash">echo $myAddRefResult</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>9[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Sub-shells ===

# A <code>sub-shell</code> is a special type of command group that allows us to spawn a new execution environment from the current shell.
# Instead of curly braces, we use <code>parentheses</code> to delimit the function body.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="31">

<source lang="bash">function add_subshell (
    # 'sum' is a global variable
    sum=$(( $1 + $2 ))
    echo $sum 
)</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="32">

<source lang="bash">add_subshell 2 3</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>5[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

Our global variable did not change because the function was executed in a sub-shell.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="34">

<source lang="bash">echo $sum</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>3[?2004l
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Recursion ===

Recursion is possible but not typical for shell programming.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="41">

<source lang="bash">function factorial {
    if [ $1 -le 1 ]; then
        echo -n 1
    else
        echo -n $(( $(factorial $(( $1 - 1 ))) * $1))
    fi 
}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="42">

<source lang="bash">factorial 5</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="43">

<source lang="bash">factorial 10</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

= Arrays =


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

== Declaring Arrays ==

There are two ways:<br>

# Declare a variable <code>explicitly</code> to be an array with <code>declare -a 'arrayname'</code>.
# Create an array <code>on the fly</code> by just assigning values.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Declaring an Array explicitly ====


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="44">

<source lang="bash"># declare array
declare -a pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="45">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Creating an Array on the Fly ====

An array is automatically created when you assign a value to a variable.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="55">

<source lang="bash"># make pioneers vanish in the void
unset pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="56">

<source lang="bash">pioneers[0]='Ken Thompson'</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="57">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

You can assign multiple values at once.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="58">

<source lang="bash">unset pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="59">

<source lang="bash">pioneers=('Ken Thompson' 'Brian Kernighan' 'Dennis Ritchie')</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="60">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Assigning Values to an Array ====

An array doesn't need to have continuous indexes.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="61">

<source lang="bash">pioneers[20]='Douglas McIlroy'</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="62">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot; [20]=&quot;Douglas McIlroy&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Accessing Array Elements ===


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

The default index is zero.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="63">

<source lang="bash">echo $pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>Ken Thompson
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

This does not work as one might expect coming from a mainstream programming language.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="64">

<source lang="bash">echo $pioneers[1]</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>Ken Thompson[1]
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

This is the correct way.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="65">

<source lang="bash">echo ${pioneers[1]}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>Brian Kernighan
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

Now the whole array:


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="66">

<source lang="bash">echo ${pioneers[@]}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>Ken Thompson Brian Kernighan Dennis Ritchie Douglas McIlroy
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="67">

<source lang="bash">echo ${pioneers[*]}</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>Ken Thompson Brian Kernighan Dennis Ritchie Douglas McIlroy
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

We&quot;ll see the difference of the two commands above when we cover looping.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="68">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot; [20]=&quot;Douglas McIlroy&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Appending an Arrays with <code>+=(another_array)</code> ===


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="71">

<source lang="bash">unset pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

You can also explicitly specify the index of the array entry.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="72">

<source lang="bash">pioneers=('Ken Thompson' 'Brian Kernighan' 'Dennis Ritchie' [20]='Douglas McIlroy')</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="73">

<source lang="bash">pioneers+=('Linus Torvals' 'Richard Stallman')</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="74">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot; [20]=&quot;Douglas McIlroy&quot; [21]=&quot;Linus Torvals&quot; [22]=&quot;Richard Stallman&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

You often see this workaround in older scripts:


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="75">

<source lang="bash">unset pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="76">

<source lang="bash">pioneers=('Ken Thompson' 'Brian Kernighan' 'Dennis Ritchie' [20]="Douglas McIlroy")</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="77">

<source lang="bash">declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot; [20]=&quot;Douglas McIlroy&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

This workaround of appending array elements works only when indices are consecutive.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="78">

<source lang="bash">pioneers=("${pioneers[@]}" 'Joe Ossanna' 'Linus Torvalds')</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="80">

<source lang="bash"># Douglas McIlroy has now index 3!
declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken Thompson&quot; [1]=&quot;Brian Kernighan&quot; [2]=&quot;Dennis Ritchie&quot; [3]=&quot;Douglas McIlroy&quot; [4]=&quot;Joe Ossanna&quot; [5]=&quot;Linus Torvalds&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

The quotes are essential!


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="81">

<source lang="bash">pioneers=(${pioneers[@]} 'Richard Stallman')</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="83">

<source lang="bash"># Every word is now a separate entry in the array.
declare -p pioneers</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>declare -a pioneers=([0]=&quot;Ken&quot; [1]=&quot;Thompson&quot; [2]=&quot;Brian&quot; [3]=&quot;Kernighan&quot; [4]=&quot;Dennis&quot; [5]=&quot;Ritchie&quot; [6]=&quot;Douglas&quot; [7]=&quot;McIlroy&quot; [8]=&quot;Joe&quot; [9]=&quot;Ossanna&quot; [10]=&quot;Linus&quot; [11]=&quot;Torvalds&quot; [12]=&quot;Richard Stallman&quot;)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Variable Substitution ===

'''Variable substitutions should only be used inside <code>double quotes</code>.'''


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="155">

<source lang="bash">calculation='2 * 3'
echo "$calculation"         # prints 2 * 3
echo $calculation           # prints 2, the list of files in the current directory, and 3
echo "$(($calculation))"    # prints 6</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>2 * 304h</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

Outside of double quotes, <code>$var</code> takes the value of var, <code>splits</code> it into whitespace-delimited parts, and interprets each part as a <code>glob</code> (wildcard) pattern. Unless you want this behavior, <code>always put $var inside double quotes: &quot;$var&quot;</code>.

The same applies to command substitutions: <code>&quot;$(mycommand)&quot;</code> is the output of mycommand, <code>$(mycommand)</code> is the result of <code>split &amp; glob</code> on the output.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

<code>echo &quot;<math display="inline">var" # good echo "</math>(mycommand)&quot; # good another=<math display="inline">var # also works, assignment is implicitly double-quoted!!! make -D THING=</math>var # BAD! This is not a bash assignment. make -D THING=&quot;<math display="inline">var" # good make -D "THING=</math>var&quot; # also good</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Command substitutions get their own quoting contexts. Writing arbitrarily nested substitutions is easy because the parser will keep track of nesting depth instead of greedily searching for the first <code>&quot;</code> character. ====


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="162">

<source lang="bash">c=3
echo "formatted text: $(printf "a + b = %04d" "${c}")" # “formatted text: a + b = 0003”</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>formatted text: a + b = 0003
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Variable arguments to a command substitution should be double-quoted inside the expansions as well ====


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="164">

<source lang="bash"># echo "$(mycommand "$arg1" "$arg2")"</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<div class="cell markdown">

= Loops, Case and Select =

# <code>For</code> Loops
# <code>For</code> Loops/<code>C-Syntax</code>
# <code>While</code> Loops
# <code>Until</code> Loops
# <code>Case</code> Command
# <code>Select</code> Command

It is easier to use double quotes all the time than to remember when they are needed. They are needed most of the time, so you'll need to learn when they aren't needed, not when they are needed.

In a nutshell, double quotes are necessary wherever a list of words or a pattern is expected. They are optional in contexts where a raw string is expected by the parser.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

== For Loops ==

General structure: <br><code> for varname in list do commands using $varname&quot; done </code>


</div>

== Case Command ==


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

General structure: <code> case $variable-name in pattern1|pattern2|pattern3)<br />
command1 ... .... commandN ;; pattern4|pattern5|pattern6) command1 ... .... commandN ;;<br />
pattern7|pattern8|patternN)<br />
command1 ... .... commandN ;; *)<br />
esac </code>


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="209">

<source lang="bash">NOW=$(date +"%a")
case $NOW in
    Mon)
        echo "FULL backup!";;
    Tue|Wed|Thu|Fri)
        echo "PARTIAL backup!";;
    Sat|Sun)
        echo "NO backup!";;
    *) ;;
esac</source>

<pre>PARTIAL backup!l</pre>

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Case terminators ===

The <code>;&amp;</code> terminator causes case to also execute the next block without testing its pattern. The <code>;;&amp;</code> operator is like <code>;;</code> except the case statement doesn't terminate after executing the associated list. Bash just continues testing the next pattern as though the previous pattern didn't match.

<div class="cell markdown">

==== Globs vs. Regular Expressions ====

Glob<br> <code>[0-9]?file''.txt</code><br><br> Regular Expression<br> <code>[0-9].file.''.txt</code>

# Globs are faster and less expressive than REs.
# Globs and REs look similar but are different.
# Globs match files!
# REs match text/strings!


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

Using a Glob with ls<br> <code>ls [0-9]?_file*.txt</code><br> will be expanded by Bash to:<br> <code>ls 1_file-rev1.txt 2_file-rev1.txt 3_file-rev1.txt</code><br> <code>ls</code> itself is unaware of this expansion!

To achieve the same with RE you had to do something like this:<br> <code>ls | grep '[0-9]._file.*.txt'</code><br>

This command uses REs and globs:<br> <code>grep '^A.''.txt' ''.txt</code> Will be expanded by Bash to:<br> <code>grep '^A.*.txt' file1.txt file2.txt </code><br> Then grep will use the RE to search for text in those files. To prevent Bash from interpreting the RE as a glob it has to be enclosed in single quotes!


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Types of Shell Expansion ====

Expansions happens in this order:

# <code>Brace</code> expansion
# <code>Tilde</code> expansion
# <code>Parameter</code> expansion
# <code>Variable</code> expansion
# <code>Arithmetic</code> expansion and <code>command substitution</code> from left to right
# <code>Word splitting</code>
# Filename expansion (expanding <code>globs</code> into lists)

Then <code>Quote removal</code> happens.

<code>Note:</code> Filename expansion which we think about most is done last!


</div>

# Brace expansion
# Word splitting
# Filename expansion


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Expansions That Do Not Change the Number of Words ====

# Arithmetic expansion
# Command substitution
# Variable expansion
# Parameter expansion


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== File Globs ====

{|
!width="50%"| File Glob
!width="50%"| Explanation
|-
| <code>*</code> (Asterisk/Star)
| Matches any number of any characters.
|-
| <code>?</code> (Question mark)
| Matches <code>EXACTLY</code> one character - can be any character.
|-
| <code>[]</code> (Character set)
| Matches exactly one character - but we define which ones.
|-
| <code>[^]</code>
| Invert the character set.
|-
| <code>[!]</code>
| Invert the character set. Same as <code>[^]</code>. Preferred as ^ can also be an anchor meaning beginning of line.
|}

==== Bash Globbing Options ====

# nullglob
# failglob
# dotglob
# globstar
# nocasematch
# nocaseglob
# extglob

To '''set''' a shell variable use: '''shopt -s'''<br> To '''unset''' a shell variable use: '''shopt -u'''<br> To '''display''' the current value use: '''shopt -p'''<br>


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="63">

<source lang="bash">shopt -p nullglob # nullglob is not set</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>shopt -u nullglob
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="64">

<source lang="bash">shopt -u nullglob # If there are no *.bin files in the directory
# it will be set to '*.bin' and found to 1
# which in our application case is wrong.
found=0
for i in *.bin; do
    echo $i
    found=1
done
echo $found</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>*.bin04h</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="65">

<source lang="bash">shopt -s nullglob # If there are no *.bin files we don't enter the for-loop. This is what we want!
found=0
for i in *.bin; do # pattern is set to null. For-loop is not entered.
    echo $i
    found=1
done
shopt -u nullglob # Immediately deactivate this option! It can break some tools and even shell scripts!
echo $found</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>0[?2004h</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>

<source lang="bash">shopt -s failglob # If there are no *.bin files an error is displayed.
found=0
for i in *.bin; do # Error is displayed and the code is not executed.
    echo $i
    found=1
done
shopt -u failglob # Immediately deactivate this option! It can break some tools and even shell scripts!
echo $found</source>

<div class="cell markdown">

==== Why You Should Use Extended Globs ====

# Make interactive globbing more useful.<br> Remove all files that start with IMG or DSC but do NOT end in .CRW or .NEF<br> <code>rm @(IMG|DSC)*!(.CRW|.NEF)</code><br> This would be difficult to do with the GUI or standard globs.
# Add more power to if conditional statements.<br> <code> if [[ $i = Backup*.@(@(tar|arc).gz|tgz) ]]; then echo $i fi</code><br> Executes much faster than the corresponding RE.
# Add more power to case statements.<br> <code> for file in ''; do case $file in @(IMG|DSC)''@(@(.CR2|.NEF).xmp|.NEF|.CR2)) (( ALLRAW++ )) ;;&amp; DSC''@(.NEF|.NEF.xmp)) (( NIKRAW++ )) ;;&amp; DSC''@(.NEF.xmp) (( NIKSUP++ )) ;; IMG''@(.CR2|.CR2.xmp) (( CANRAW++ )) ;;&amp; IMG''@(.CR2.xmp) (( CANSUP++ )) ;; IMG''@(.JPG|.jpg)) (( CANJPG++ )) ;; '') (( OTHER++ )) ;; esac done </code> <br> We cannot use REs in case statements! This can be epic!
# Add more power to pattern substitution.<br> <code> file=Archive-2017-06-12.tar.gz echo ${file%%@(.tar|.bak)*} -&gt; Archive-2017-06-12</code>
# Speed!<br> Extended globs are much faster than REs. So if you can use an extended glob instead of an RE do it!


</div>

<div class="cell markdown">

### Extended Globs vs. Regular Expressions #### Extended Globs:

# match files
# for loops
# if conditionals
# case statements
# variable pattern matching

#### Regular Expressions:

# match text
# grep
# awk
# sed
# if [[ =~ ]]


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

{|
! Extended Glob
! Regular Expression
|-
| <code>@(pattern)</code>
| <code>(pattern)</code>
|-
| <code>?(pattern)</code>
| <code>(pattern)?</code>
|-
| <code>+(pattern)</code>
| <code>(pattern)+</code>
|-
| <code>*(pattern)</code>
| <code>(pattern)*)</code>
|-
| <code>!(pattern)</code>
| <code>(!pattern)</code>
|-
| <code>*(pattern1\|pattern2)</code>
| <code>(pattern1\|pattern2)*</code>
|-
| <code>N/A!!!</code>
| <code>(pattern){3}</code>
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Brace Expansion vs. Globs ====

# Globs expand pathnames
# Brace expansion expands braces
# Brace expansion is processed first
# Globs are processed last
# Brace expansion does <code>NOT</code> depend on file existence
# Brace expansion is a <code>pure string operation</code>


</div>

<div class="cell markdown">

= Regular Expressions =

# POSIX Standards
## BRE: Basic Regular Expressions
### BREs came first
## ERE: Extended Regular Expressions
### EREs were extended
### EREs and BREs became similar over the years
### However, EREs are cleaner and simpler to read
# PCRE: Perl Compatible Regular Expressions
## Ungreedy matches
## Multiline matches
## JIT compiler support
## Subroutines
## Named patterns
## Lookahead assertions
## Lookbehind assertions
## Recursive patterns
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_regular-expression_engines


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Typical Shell Tools That Support Regexes ===

# grep
# awk
# sed
# bash

Support for regexes varies: http://www.regular-expressions.info/refcharacters.html


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Regular Expression Support ===

# http://www.regular-expressions.info/refflavors.html
# Support differs in each regex engine
# Implementations may differ of the same engine
# Be ready to experiment


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== ERE Syntax ===

{|
! Special Character
! Function
|-
| .
| matches one character
|-
| []
| character sets
|-
| \
| escape single characters
|-
| ()
| pattern grouping
|-
| |
| alternation
|-
| *+{}
| repetition operators
|-
| '''^'''abc
| leading anchor
|-
| abc'''$'''
| trailing anchor
|-
| ['''^'''abc]
| negates pattern
|-
| '''['''{''']'''
| escape special characters
|-
| '''\'''{
| escape special characters
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== BRE Syntax ===

# With BREs you have to escape RE characters to make them special!
# Which results in a backslash binge!
# BREs cannot do alternation
# With GNU tools, both BREs and EREs are equal!
# Use EREs whenever possible.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Regex Support in GNU Tools ===

# GNU Tools use BREs by default!

{|
! Tool
! Regex Type
! Comment
|-
| grep, grep -G
| BRE
|
|-
| grep '''-E'''
| ERE
| egrep is the same, but regarded as obsolete and still around
|-
| sed
| BRE
|
|-
| sed '''-E'''
| ERE
|
|-
| awk
| ERE
| awk only uses EREs
|-
| Bash [[ =~ ]]
| ERE
|
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Matching Single Characters ===

{|
!width="33%"| Pattern
!width="33%"| Match
!width="33%"| Comment
|-
| .
| one character
|
|-
| [abc]
| one character in list
|
|-
| [^abc]
| one character not in list
|
|-
| [0-9]
| one number in range
|
|-
| [:alpha:]
| one character in class
|
|-
| \b
| empty string at either word edge
| \brat\b not same as [[:space:]rat[:space:]]. The latter includes the spaces in the match, the first doesn't.
|-
| \B
| empty string not at word edge
| \Brat\B matches &quot;c'''rat'''e&quot; but not &quot;furry rat&quot;.
|-
| \&lt;
| empty string at beginning of word
|
|-
| \&gt;
| empty string at end of word
|
|-
| \w
| match whole word
| \wrat would match &quot;'''crate'''&quot; and &quot;'''crateandbarrel'''&quot; and matches the whole words!
|-
| \W
| match a non-word
|
|-
| \s
| match a whitespace
| same as [[:space:]]
|-
| \S
| match a non-whitespace
|
|-
| ^
| anchor to the beginning of the line
|
|-
| $
| anchor to the end of the line
|
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

Matching Occurrences

{|
! Pattern
! Match
! Comment
|-
| .
| one character
|
|-
| .?
| zero or one occurrence
|
|-
| .+
| one or more occurrences
|
|-
| .*
| zero or more occurrences
|
|-
| .{3}
| three occurrences
|
|-
| .{3,}
| three or more occurrences
|
|-
| .{,3}
| zero to three occurrences
|
|-
| .{1,3}
| one to three occurrences
|
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Alternation and Grouping ===

# Alternation allows matching one or another
## '''dog|cat''' matches dog, cat, dogdog, catcat due to concatenation and greedy matches!
## '''^(dog|cat)?$''' matches dog, cat but not dogdog nor catcat
## '''^(dog|cat)+$''' matches dog, cat, dogdog, catcat
## Numbers 1-99:
### Numbers 0-9: [0-9]
### Numbers 10-99: [1-9][0-9]
### Numbers 1-99: [0-9]|[1-9][0-9]
## Numbers 0-99: [0-9][0-9]?
## Numbers 0-150:
### Numbers 0-99: [0-9][0-9]?
### Numbers 100-149: 1[0-4][0-9]
### Number 150: 150
### Numbers 0-150: ^(150|1[0-4][0-9]|[0-9][0-9]?)$
#### We go from most specific to least specific!
# Grouping treats more than one pattern as one match


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Backreferences ===

# Maximum of nine backreferences from \1 to \9.
# (ss).*\1.*\1 would match cla'''sslessness''', posse'''ssiveness''', stre'''sslessness'''
# Five-letter palindromes: ^(.)(.).\2\1$ would match radar, civil, kayak, level


</div>

<source lang="bash"># Finding Visa card numbers & print them
# Adding hyphens every four digits for easier reading
for line in $(cat sales.csv); do
    if [[ $line =~ .*[Vv]isa.*  ]]; then
        if [[ $line =~ [0-9]{16} ]]; then
            echo ${BASH_REMATCH[0]} | sed -E 's/([0-9]{4})([0-9]{4})([0-9]{4})([0-9]{4})/\1-\2-\3-\4/'
        fi
        
    fi
done</source>

=== Grep Options ===

{|
!width="33%"| Option
!width="33%"| Function
!width="33%"| Comments
|-
| grep -E or egrep
| Process as ERE
| You can also use egrep although it is deprecated but kept around for historical reason.
|-
|
|
| GNU grep supports backreferences in EREs!
|-
| grep -G
| Process as BRE
|
|-
| grep -P
| Process as PCRE
| There is also the '''pcregrep''' utility.
|-
| grep -e &quot;pattern&quot;
| Use <pattern> as the pattern
| Used when facing command line parsing problems when pattern starts with a hyphen.
|-
| grep -f &quot;file&quot;
| Get patterns from a file
| One pattern per line. All of them will be applied.
|-
| grep -w
| Match only whole words
| Similar to patterns with \b.
|-
| grep -x
| Match only whole lines
|
|-
| grep -o
| Only return the matched text not the whole line
|
|-
| grep -p
| Do not return the match, only the return code
| Useful in conditionals.
|-
| grep -z
| Replace newline by NULL
| Useful in multline matching using PCREs.
|}

=== Performance Optimizing Grep ===

# Change the locale to C
# For non C locales, avoid [a-z] and [[=a=]]
# Avoid backreferences
# Don't use grep -i
# Simplify searches.
#* Multiple simple piped searches can be faster than one complex search
#* grep uses '''Boyer-Moore''' fast string search algorithm for single fixed pattern
#* grep uses the '''Aho–Corasick''' algorithm for muliple fixed patterns


</div>

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Sed is a stream editor ===

* http://sed.sourceforge.net/
** sed one liners: http://sed.sourceforge.net/sed1line.txt
* Which means that it handles text on the fly!
* If you know Vim's Excommand mode you know most of sed!


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== sed Modes ====

* Print
* Delete
* Substitute


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Printing with BRE ====

* -n prints out only matched lines
* sed -n '/BRE regex/p'
* sed -n -E '/ERE regex/p'


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Getting Data into sed ====

# Piping: <code>cat /etc/password | sed -n '/BRE regex/p'</code>
# Input from a file: <code>sed -n 'BRE regex/p' /etc/passwd</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Output to a File ====

<code>sed -n '/BRE regex/p' /etc/passwd &gt; newpasswd</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== In-Place Editing ====

<code>sed -n -i '/BRE regex/p' /etc/passwd</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Deleting Text ====

* <code>sed '/BRE regex/d'</code>
* <code>sed -E '/ERE regex/d'</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Substituting Text ====

* <code>sed 's/BRE regex/BRE regex/g'</code>
* <code>sed -E 's/ERE regex/ERE regex/g'</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Addresses and Address Ranges ====

* Line to match
* Range of lines to match
* Negation
* Every nth line
* Examples:
** Print lines 5 to 10: <code>sed '5,10p'</code>
** Delete lines 5 to 10: <code>sed '5,10d'</code>
** Substitute on lines 5 to 10: <code>sed '5,10s/BRE regex/BRE regex/g'</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== sed Substitution Flags ====

{|
! Option
! Function
|-
| g
| replace every instance on the line - globally to the line
|-
| NUMBER
| replace the nth match
|-
| p
| after the substitution print
|-
| w
| after the substitution print to a file
|-
| i
| case insensitive
|}


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

==== Alternate String Separator ====

* Use any different character that does not have special meaning in a regular expression.
** <code>sed 's/BRE regex/BRE regex/g'</code>
** <code>sed 's/\/path\/to\/file.txt/\/path\/to\/file.jpg/g' # Uff!!!</code>
** <code>sed 's:/path/to/file.txt:/path/to/file.jpg:g' # Much easier!</code>


</div>

<source lang="bash"># Using Bash with EXACTLY the same regex!

function findIPs {
for i in $(cat IPaddresses.csv); do
    if [[ $i =~  ((1?[0-9][0-9]?|2[0-4][0-9]|25[0-5])\.){3}(1?[0-9][0-9]?|2[0-4][0-9]|25[0-5]) ]]; then
        echo ${BASH_REMATCH[0]}
    fi
done
}

findIPs | tail</source>

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Bash Startup Files ===

* In this order for '''interactive login shells''':
** <code>/etc/profile</code>
** <code>~/.bash_profile</code>
** <code>~/.bash_login</code>
** <code>~/.profile</code>
* <code>~.bashrc</code> is typically called from <code>.bash_profile</code>
* In this order for '''interactive non-login shells''':
** <code>~/.bashrc</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Three Types of Bash Parameters ===

# Variables
#* Created by the user
# Special Parameters
#* Predefined by Bash and read-only
# Positional Parameters
#* Arguments given to shell scripts
#* <code>$1 to $9, ${10}, ${11}, ...</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Variable Basics ===

* No Space before or after the equal sign:
** <code>USERNAME=schmidh</code>
** If you used <code>USERNAME = schmidh</code> the shell would try to execute the command <code>USERNAME</code>!
** If you used <code>USERNAME= schmidh</code> the shell would assign an empty value to <code>USERNAME</code> and would try to execute the command <code>schmidh</code>!

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Quoting vs. Not-Quoting (<code>&quot;$VAR&quot; vs $VAR</code>) ===

# If you quote it is considered one word.
# if you don't quote it will be split into multiple words.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="48">

<source lang="bash">states="CA NY UT TX"</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="51">

<source lang="bash"># no quotes around $states
for i in $states; do
    echo $i
done</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>CA?2004h</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="54">

<source lang="bash"># With quotes it is regarded as one word
for i in "$states"; do
    echo $i
done</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>CA NY UT TX2004l</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Shell Script Arguments ===

# Special Parameters
#* Name of the script: <code>$0</code>
#* All parameters: <code>$*</code>
#* All parameters: <code>$@</code>
#* Total number of parameters: <code>$#</code>
# Positional Parameters
#* Arguments given to shell scripts
#** <code>$1 to $9, ${10}, ${11}, ...</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Difference between <code>$*</code> and <code>$@</code> ===

They behave exactly the same except when you double quote them. When you double quote <code>&quot;$*&quot;</code>, it is converted to <code>&quot;${1}x${2}x${3}x...&quot;</code>. In this, x is the first character of the IFS variable which can be changed. <code>$@</code> always uses a space.

'''IFS''' = '''Internal Field Separator''' - Default value is <code>&lt;space&gt;&lt;tab&gt;&lt;newline&gt;</code>


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Getting Range of Parameters ===

<code>${@:$start:$count}</code>

<code>$count</code> is optional. When you don't provide <code>$count</code>, bash extracts all the remaining arguments from <code>$start</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Shift Command ===

<code>shift [n]</code>

The Shift command moves the arguments (positional parameters) to the left by <code>n</code> positions. If you don't specify <code>n</code>, the arguments will be moved by 1.


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== Bash Special Parameters ===

{|
!width="50%"| Special Parameter
!width="50%"| Description
|-
| <code>$*</code>
| Contains all the positional parameters.
|-
| <code>$@</code>
| Same as above. Contains all the positional parameters.
|-
| <code>$#</code>
| Total number of positional parameters. i.e total number of arguments passed to the shell script.
|-
| <code>$$</code>
| Contains the PID of the shell.
|-
| <code>$!</code>
| Contains the PID of the most recently executed background process.
|-
| <code>$?</code>
| Contains the exit status of the most recently executed command.
|-
| <code>$-</code>
| Contains all the options set using the bash set builtin command.
|-
| <code>$_</code>
| Gives the last argument to the previous command. At the shell startup, it gives the absolute filename of the shell script being executed.
|}


</div>

=== Let or (( )) or expr -- which one to use? ===

* In general, use either let or (( )).
* (( )) is highly preferred due to its readability.
* Avoid the expr command because it is really calling a unix command to evaluate the arithmetic expression. That means it will unnecessarily spawn a new process.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="140">

<source lang="bash"># All three achieve the same.
let total=total+2
((total=total+2))
total=`expr $total + 2`
echo $total</source>

</div>

=== Mathematical Operators ===

* Bash does not understand floating point arithmetic. It treats numbers containing a decimal point as strings. This restriction applies even if you use let, (( )), or expr.
* Operators and their precedence:

{|
! Operator
! Description
|-
| <code>var++</code>, <code>var--</code>
| Post auto increment and auto decrement
|-
| <code>++var</code>, <code>--var</code>
| Pre auto increment and auto decrement
|-
| <code>-</code>, <code>+</code>
| Unary minus and plus
|-
| <code>!</code>, <code>~</code>
| Logical and bitwise negation
|-
| <code>**</code>
| Exponentiation
|-
| <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, <code>%</code>
| Multiply, divide, and modulo operator
|-
| <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>
| Add and subtract
|-
| <code>&lt;&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;</code>
| Bit-wise left and right shift
|-
| <code>&lt;=</code>, <code>&gt;=</code>, <code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>
| Comparisons
|-
| <code>==</code>, <code>!=</code>
| Equal-to and not-equal-to
|-
| <code>&amp;</code> <code>^</code> <code>|</code>
| Operators in the same order mentioned here. AND, XOR, OR
|-
| <code>&amp;&amp;</code>
| Logical AND
|-
| <code>||</code>
| Logical OR
|-
| <code>expr ? expr : expr</code>
| Ternary operator
|-
| <code>=</code>, <code>*=</code>, <code>/=</code>, <code>%=</code>, <code>+=</code>, <code>-=</code>, <code>&lt;&lt;=</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;=</code>, <code>&amp;=</code>, <code>^=</code>,<code>\|=</code>
| Assignments
|}

Inside an <code>if</code> statement, when an arithmetic expression's result is <code>0</code>, it is considered false, and when an arithmetic expression's result is anything except <code>0</code>, it is considered true.

{|
! File Test Operator

|-

|-

|-

|-

|-
| -S

|-

|-
| -r
| file has read permission

| -w
| file has write permission
|-

| file has execute permission
|-

|-
| -g

|-
| -k

|-
| -O

|-
| -G

|-
| -N
| Did the file got modified since last read?
|-
| file1 -nt file2
| file1 is newer than file2
|-
| file1 -ot file2
| file1 is older than file2
|-
| file1 -ef file2
| Both file1 and file2 are hard linked to the same file
|}

Note: You can reverse the meaning of any of the above conditions by adding a <code>!</code> in front of them.

# command1 <code>&amp;&amp;</code> command2 <code>&amp;&amp;</code> command3 <code>&amp;&amp;</code> ...
# If command1 <code>succeeds</code> (with a <code>return status of 0</code>), command2 will be executed. And so on...

=== <code>||</code> - Combine Multiple Commands with OR ===

# command1 <code>||</code> command2 <code>||</code> command3 <code>||</code> ...
# If command1 <code>fails</code> (<code>return status of non zero</code>), command2 will be executed. And so on...


</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

=== <code>[[ ]]</code> - Extended Test Command ===

<code>[[ ]]</code> is the extended test command, an advanced variation of the <code>[ ]</code> command that does everything <code>[ ]</code> does, plus the following:

* Pattern matching in the string comparison, when you use <code>=</code>, <code>==</code>, or <code>!=</code>
* <code>=~</code> inside extended test command
* <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> inside the extended test command
* <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&gt;</code> for comparison inside the extended test command
* enclosing an expression in <code>( )</code> to change its evaluation precedence
* <code>Tilde expansion</code>, <code>arithmetic expansion</code>, and <code>parameter expansion</code>
* <code>Command substitution</code> and <code>process substitution</code>


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="117">

<source lang="bash">name="bond"
# 1. You can use pattern matching in [[ ]]
[ $name = bon* ] && echo "1.1. Good Morning, Mr. Bond"      # does not work with basic test
[[ $name = bon* ]] && echo "1.2. Good Morning, Mr. Bond"

# 2. You can use || && inside [[ ]]
[[ $name = super || $name = bon* ]] && echo "2. Good Morning, Mr. Hero"

# 3. You can use =~ for regular expression inside [[ ]]
[[ $name =~ ^b ]] && echo "3. Mr. $name, your name starts with "b""

i=1
for item in /etc/*.conf; do
    [[ $item =~ ^/etc/s.* ]] && echo "Config file $((i++)): $item"
done

i=1
for item in ~/Pictures/*; do
    [[ $item = *.jpg ]] && echo "Image $((i++)): $item"
done</source>

<div class="cell markdown">

==== If you want both output and error to be redirected to the same output file, use <code>&amp;&gt;</code> / <code>&gt;&amp;</code> or <code>&amp;&gt;&gt;</code> / <code>&gt;&gt;&amp;</code>! ====

# <code>&amp;&gt;</code> and <code>&gt;&amp;</code> are the same.
# <code>&amp;&gt;&gt;</code> and <code>&gt;&gt;&amp;</code> are the same.
# <code>2&gt;&amp;1</code> means file descriptor 2 is redirected to file descriptor 1, which means, standard error is also redirected to standard output. So, if standard output was pointed to a file, the standard error will also be pointed to the same file where the standard output is pointing.
# Order of redirection is important.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="130">

<source lang="bash"># Error Redirection
# Using output redirection >, we can send the output of any command to a file.
# However, when the command displays an error, that doesn't go to the redirected file.
ls -l /etc/doesnotexist.conf > /tmp/output1.txt
cat /tmp/output1.txt</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>ls: cannot access '/etc/doesnotexist.conf': No such file or directory
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="136">

<source lang="bash"># We have to redirect the error messages.
ls -l /etc/doesnotexist.conf &>> /tmp/output1.txt      # append mode (>>)
ls -l /etc/doesnotexist.conf  >> /tmp/output1.txt 2>&1 # the same</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre></pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

</div>
<div class="cell markdown">

<code>ls -l /etc/doesnotexist.conf 2&gt;&amp;1 &gt;/tmp/1.txt</code>

Means something different.

* <code>2&gt;&amp;1</code> indicates that standard error <code>(2&gt;)</code> is redirected to the same file descriptor associated with standard output <code>(&amp;1)</code>. Since standard output at this stage is the terminal, the error messages go to the terminal, and not to the <code>/tmp/1.txt</code> file that comes next.
* <code>&gt;/tmp/1.txt</code> redirects standard output, so the output would go to the <code>/tmp/1.txt</code> file. <code>However, standard error was already redirected, and is not changed!!!</code>


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="137">

<source lang="bash">cat /tmp/output1.txt</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>ls: cannot access '/etc/doesnotexist.conf': No such file or directory
ls: cannot access '/etc/doesnotexist.conf': No such file or directory
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output error" ename="" evalue="1">

<pre></pre>

</div>

=== Process List ===

Process substitution creates a named pipe under /dev/fd, which is used by multiple commands to write the output, and the other command to read from it for its input.

* <code>&gt;(list-of-commands)</code> will read the input from <code>/dev/fd/xx</code>
* <code>&lt;(list-of-commands)</code> will write the output to <code>/dev/fd/xx</code>


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="170">

<source lang="bash"># Do this in a real shell
# wc -l <(ls /etc/; cat /etc/passwd; echo "Hello World")</source>

# diff <(ls) <(ls -a)

# echo command in front of the above diff statement, you can see that it
# is really doing the diff between the two /dev/fd/xx streams that contain

=== Command Grouping with <code>()</code> and <code>{}</code> ===

* ( command1; command2; .... commandn )
* { command1; command2; .... commandn; }

'''Note''': It is very important to note that the <code>semi-colon</code> after the last command <code>is required</code> within the <code>{ }</code> grouping.

<code>()</code> creates a <code>sub-shell</code> and executes all the commands that are enclosed in that new <code>sub-shell environment</code>. <code>{}</code> doesn't create a sub shell. Bash executes all the commands that are enclosed in the <code>current shell environment</code>.

<code>{ }</code> is extremely useful when you combine it with <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code>.


</div>
<div class="cell code" execution_count="3">

<source lang="bash">file=/tmp/tmpfile.txt
touch $file
[ -e $file ] && { rm $file || echo "Unable to delete $file"; }</source>

    c=&quot;$branch_color$c&quot;;
    z=&quot;$c_clear$z&quot;;

    if [ -n &quot;$s&quot; ]; then
        s=&quot;$flags_color$s&quot;;
    fi;
    if [ -n &quot;$u&quot; ]; then
        u=&quot;$bad_color$u&quot;;
    fi;
    r=&quot;$c_clear$r&quot;
}

    local i c=1 only_local_ref=&quot;n&quot; has_r=&quot;n&quot;;
    while [ $c -lt $cword ]; do
        i=&quot;${words[c]}&quot;;
        case &quot;$i&quot; in 
            -d | -m)
                only_local_ref=&quot;y&quot;
            ;;
            -r)
                has_r=&quot;y&quot;
            ;;
        esac;
        ((c++));
    done;
    case &quot;$cur&quot; in 
        --set-upstream-to=*)
            __gitcomp_nl &quot;$(__git_refs)&quot; &quot;&quot; &quot;${cur##--set-upstream-to=}&quot;
        ;;
        --*)
            __gitcomp &quot;
			--color --no-color --verbose --abbrev= --no-abbrev
			--track --no-track --contains --merged --no-merged
			--set-upstream-to= --edit-description --list
			--unset-upstream
			&quot;
        ;;
        *)
            if [ $only_local_ref = &quot;y&quot; -a $has_r = &quot;n&quot; ]; then
                __gitcomp_nl &quot;$(__git_heads)&quot;;
            else
                __gitcomp_nl &quot;$(__git_refs)&quot;;
            fi
        ;;
    esac
}
_git_bundle () 
{ 
    local cmd=&quot;${words[2]}&quot;;
    case &quot;$cword&quot; in 
        2)

        ;;
        3)

        ;;

            esac
        ;;
    esac
}
_git_checkout () 
{ 
    __git_has_doubledash &amp;&amp; return;
    case &quot;$cur&quot; in 
        --conflict=*)
            __gitcomp &quot;diff3 merge&quot; &quot;&quot; &quot;${cur##--conflict=}&quot;
        ;;
        --*)
            __gitcomp &quot;
			--quiet --ours --theirs --track --no-track --merge
			--conflict= --orphan --patch
			&quot;
        ;;
        *)
            local flags=&quot;--track --no-track --no-guess&quot; track=1;
            if [ -n &quot;$(__git_find_on_cmdline &quot;$flags&quot;)&quot; ]; then
                track='';
            fi;
            __gitcomp_nl &quot;$(__git_refs '' $track)&quot;

    esac
}
_git_cherry ()

    } else if ($0 ~ /^\?\? .+/) {

  }
  END {
    if (!seen_header) {
      print

    print untracked &quot;\t&quot; unstaged &quot;\t&quot; staged
  }'
}

<div class="cell markdown">

=== Coproc Builtin ===

<code>coproc [NAME] command</code>

Using <code>coproc</code> you can start a background process and interact with its input and output. This is just like starting a job in the background with <code>&amp;</code>, however with the coproc builtin you can establish <code>two-way communication</code> between the background process and the shell that created the process.

Coproc creates the following three environment variables.

* <code>NAME_PID</code> that stores the <code>process id</code> of the background process that was called using coproc.
* <code>NAME[0]</code> contains the file descriptor for the <code>standard output</code> of the background process
* <code>NAME[1]</code> contains the file descriptor for the <code>standard input</code> of the background process.

If you don't specify a name for the coproc, the default name is <code>COPROC</code>.


</div>

<source lang="bash">coproc CUSTOM { ls -l; sleep 2; cat /etc/passwd; sleep 2; }
echo "CUSTOM_PID=$CUSTOM_PID"
echo "CUSTOM[0]=${CUSTOM[0]}"
echo "CUSTOM[1]=${CUSTOM[1]}"</source>

<source lang="bash"># See all OS signals
man 7 signal</source>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>SIGNAL(7)                  Linux Programmer's Manual                 SIGNAL(7)



NAME
       signal - overview of signals

DESCRIPTION
       Linux supports both POSIX reliable signals (hereinafter &quot;standard
       signals&quot;) and POSIX real-time signals.

   Signal dispositions
       Each signal has a current disposition, which determines how the process
       behaves when it is delivered the signal.

       The entries in the &quot;Action&quot; column of the table below specify the
       default disposition for each signal, as follows:

       Term   Default action is to terminate the process.

       Ign    Default action is to ignore the signal.

       Core   Default action is to terminate the process and dump core (see
              core(5)).

       Stop   Default action is to stop the process.

       Cont   Default action is to continue the process if it is currently
              stopped.

       A process can change the disposition of a signal using sigaction(2) or
       signal(2).  (The latter is less portable when establishing a signal
       handler; see signal(2) for details.)  Using these system calls, a
       process can elect one of the following behaviors to occur on delivery
       of the signal: perform the default action; ignore the signal; or catch
       the signal with a signal handler, a programmer-defined function that is
       automatically invoked when the signal is delivered.

       By default, a signal handler is invoked on the normal process stack.
       It is possible to arrange that the signal handler uses an alternate
       stack; see sigaltstack(2) for a discussion of how to do this and when
       it might be useful.

       The signal disposition is a per-process attribute: in a multithreaded
       application, the disposition of a particular signal is the same for all
       threads.

       A child created via fork(2) inherits a copy of its parent's signal
       dispositions.  During an execve(2), the dispositions of handled signals
       are reset to the default; the dispositions of ignored signals are left
       unchanged.

   Sending a signal
       The following system calls and library functions allow the caller to
       send a signal:

       raise(3)
              Sends a signal to the calling thread.

       kill(2)
              Sends a signal to a specified process, to all members of a
              specified process group, or to all processes on the system.

       pidfd_send_signal(2)
              Sends a signal to a process identified by a PID file descriptor.

       killpg(3)
              Sends a signal to all of the members of a specified process
              group.

       pthread_kill(3)
              Sends a signal to a specified POSIX thread in the same process
              as the caller.

       tgkill(2)
              Sends a signal to a specified thread within a specific process.
              (This is the system call used to implement pthread_kill(3).)

       sigqueue(3)
              Sends a real-time signal with accompanying data to a specified
              process.

   Waiting for a signal to be caught
       The following system calls suspend execution of the calling thread
       until a signal is caught (or an unhandled signal terminates the
       process):

       pause(2)
              Suspends execution until any signal is caught.

       sigsuspend(2)
              Temporarily changes the signal mask (see below) and suspends
              execution until one of the unmasked signals is caught.

   Synchronously accepting a signal
       Rather than asynchronously catching a signal via a signal handler, it
       is possible to synchronously accept the signal, that is, to block
       execution until the signal is delivered, at which point the kernel
       returns information about the signal to the caller.  There are two
       general ways to do this:

       * sigwaitinfo(2), sigtimedwait(2), and sigwait(3) suspend execution
         until one of the signals in a specified set is delivered.  Each of
         these calls returns information about the delivered signal.

       * signalfd(2) returns a file descriptor that can be used to read
         information about signals that are delivered to the caller.  Each
         read(2) from this file descriptor blocks until one of the signals in
         the set specified in the signalfd(2) call is delivered to the caller.
         The buffer returned by read(2) contains a structure describing the
         signal.

   Signal mask and pending signals
       A signal may be blocked, which means that it will not be delivered
       until it is later unblocked.  Between the time when it is generated and
       when it is delivered a signal is said to be pending.

       Each thread in a process has an independent signal mask, which
       indicates the set of signals that the thread is currently blocking.  A
       thread can manipulate its signal mask using pthread_sigmask(3).  In a
       traditional single-threaded application, sigprocmask(2) can be used to
       manipulate the signal mask.

       A child created via fork(2) inherits a copy of its parent's signal
       mask; the signal mask is preserved across execve(2).

       A signal may be process-directed or thread-directed.  A process-
       directed signal is one that is targeted at (and thus pending for) the
       process as a whole.  A signal may be process-directed because it was
       generated by the kernel for reasons other than a hardware exception, or
       because it was sent using kill(2) or sigqueue(3).  A thread-directed
       signal is one that is targeted at a specific thread.  A signal may be
       thread-directed because it was generated as a consequence of executing
       a specific machine-language instruction that triggered a hardware
       exception (e.g., SIGSEGV for an invalid memory access, or SIGFPE for a
       math error), or because it was targeted at a specific thread using
       interfaces such as tgkill(2) or pthread_kill(3).

       A process-directed signal may be delivered to any one of the threads
       that does not currently have the signal blocked.  If more than one of
       the threads has the signal unblocked, then the kernel chooses an
       arbitrary thread to which to deliver the signal.

       A thread can obtain the set of signals that it currently has pending
       using sigpending(2).  This set will consist of the union of the set of
       pending process-directed signals and the set of signals pending for the
       calling thread.

       A child created via fork(2) initially has an empty pending signal set;
       the pending signal set is preserved across an execve(2).

   Execution of signal handlers
       Whenever there is a transition from kernel-mode to user-mode execution
       (e.g., on return from a system call or scheduling of a thread onto the
       CPU), the kernel checks whether there is a pending unblocked signal for
       which the process has established a signal handler.  If there is such a
       pending signal, the following steps occur:

       1. The kernel performs the necessary preparatory steps for execution of
          the signal handler:

          a) The signal is removed from the set of pending signals.

          b) If the signal handler was installed by a call to sigaction(2)
             that specified the SA_ONSTACK flag and the thread has defined an
             alternate signal stack (using sigaltstack(2)), then that stack is
             installed.

          c) Various pieces of signal-related context are saved into a special
             frame that is created on the stack.  The saved information
             includes:

             + the program counter register (i.e., the address of the next
               instruction in the main program that should be executed when
               the signal handler returns);

             + architecture-specific register state required for resuming the
               interrupted program;

             + the thread's current signal mask;

             + the thread's alternate signal stack settings.

             (If the signal handler was installed using the sigaction(2)
</pre>

</div>
<div class="output stream stdout">

<pre>             SA_SIGINFO flag, then the above information is accessible via the
             ucontext_t object that is pointed to by the third argument of the
             signal handler.)

          d) Any signals specified in act-&gt;sa_mask when registering the
             handler with sigprocmask(2) are added to the thread's signal
             mask.  The signal being delivered is also added to the signal
             mask, unless SA_NODEFER was specified when registering the
             handler.  These signals are thus blocked while the handler
             executes.

       2. The kernel constructs a frame for the signal handler on the stack.
          The kernel sets the program counter for the thread to point to the
          first instruction of the signal handler function, and configures the
          return address for that function to point to a piece of user-space
          code known as the signal trampoline (described in sigreturn(2)).

       3. The kernel passes control back to user-space, where execution
          commences at the start of the signal handler function.

       4. When the signal handler returns, control passes to the signal
          trampoline code.

       5. The signal trampoline calls sigreturn(2), a system call that uses
          the information in the stack frame created in step 1 to restore the
          thread to its state before the signal handler was called.  The
          thread's signal mask and alternate signal stack settings are
          restored as part of this procedure.  Upon completion of the call to
          sigreturn(2), the kernel transfers control back to user space, and
          the thread recommences execution at the point where it was
          interrupted by the signal handler.

       Note that if the signal handler does not return (e.g., control is
       transferred out of the handler using siglongjmp(3), or the handler
       executes a new program with execve(2)), then the final step is not
       performed.  In particular, in such scenarios it is the programmer's
       responsibility to restore the state of the signal mask (using
       sigprocmask(2)), if it is desired to unblock the signals that were
       blocked on entry to the signal handler.  (Note that siglongjmp(3) may
       or may not restore the signal mask, depending on the savesigs value
       that was specified in the corresponding call to sigsetjmp(3).)

       From the kernel's point of view, execution of the signal handler code
       is exactly the same as the execution of any other user-space code.
       That is to say, the kernel does not record any special state
       information indicating that the thread is currently excuting inside a
       signal handler.  All necessary state information is maintained in user-
       space registers and the user-space stack.  The depth to which nested
       signal handlers may be invoked is thus limited only by the user-space
       stack (and sensible software design!).

   Standard signals
       Linux supports the standard signals listed below.  The second column of
       the table indicates which standard (if any) specified the signal:
       &quot;P1990&quot; indicates that the signal is described in the original
       POSIX.1-1990 standard; &quot;P2001&quot; indicates that the signal was added in
       SUSv2 and POSIX.1-2001.

       Signal      Standard   Action   Comment
       ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
       SIGABRT      P1990      Core    Abort signal from abort(3)
       SIGALRM      P1990      Term    Timer signal from alarm(2)
       SIGBUS       P2001      Core    Bus error (bad memory access)
       SIGCHLD      P1990      Ign     Child stopped or terminated
       SIGCLD         -        Ign     A synonym for SIGCHLD
       SIGCONT      P1990      Cont    Continue if stopped
       SIGEMT         -        Term    Emulator trap
       SIGFPE       P1990      Core    Floating-point exception
       SIGHUP       P1990      Term    Hangup detected on controlling terminal
                                       or death of controlling process
       SIGILL       P1990      Core    Illegal Instruction
       SIGINFO        -                A synonym for SIGPWR
       SIGINT       P1990      Term    Interrupt from keyboard
       SIGIO          -        Term    I/O now possible (4.2BSD)
       SIGIOT         -        Core    IOT trap. A synonym for SIGABRT
       SIGKILL      P1990      Term    Kill signal
       SIGLOST        -        Term    File lock lost (unused)
       SIGPIPE      P1990      Term    Broken pipe: write to pipe with no
                                       readers; see pipe(7)
       SIGPOLL      P2001      Term    Pollable event (Sys V);
                                       synonym for SIGIO
       SIGPROF      P2001      Term    Profiling timer expired
       SIGPWR         -        Term    Power failure (System V)
       SIGQUIT      P1990      Core    Quit from keyboard
       SIGSEGV      P1990      Core    Invalid memory reference
       SIGSTKFLT      -        Term    Stack fault on coprocessor (unused)
       SIGSTOP      P1990      Stop    Stop process
       SIGTSTP      P1990      Stop    Stop typed at terminal
       SIGSYS       P2001      Core    Bad system call (SVr4);
                                       see also seccomp(2)
       SIGTERM      P1990      Term    Termination signal
       SIGTRAP      P2001      Core    Trace/breakpoint trap
       SIGTTIN      P1990      Stop    Terminal input for background process
       SIGTTOU      P1990      Stop    Terminal output for background process
       SIGUNUSED      -        Core    Synonymous with SIGSYS
       SIGURG       P2001      Ign     Urgent condition on socket (4.2BSD)
       SIGUSR1      P1990      Term    User-defined signal 1
       SIGUSR2      P1990      Term    User-defined signal 2
       SIGVTALRM    P2001      Term    Virtual alarm clock (4.2BSD)
       SIGXCPU      P2001      Core    CPU time limit exceeded (4.2BSD);
                                       see setrlimit(2)
       SIGXFSZ      P2001      Core    File size limit exceeded (4.2BSD);
                                       see setrlimit(2)
       SIGWINCH       -        Ign     Window resize signal (4.3BSD, Sun)

       The signals SIGKILL and SIGSTOP cannot be caught, blocked, or ignored.

       Up to and including Linux 2.2, the default behavior for SIGSYS,
       SIGXCPU, SIGXFSZ, and (on architectures other than SPARC and MIPS)
       SIGBUS was to terminate the process (without a core dump).  (On some
       other UNIX systems the default action for SIGXCPU and SIGXFSZ is to
       terminate the process without a core dump.)  Linux 2.4 conforms to the
       POSIX.1-2001 requirements for these signals, terminating the process
       with a core dump.

       SIGEMT is not specified in POSIX.1-2001, but nevertheless appears on
       most other UNIX systems, where its default action is typically to
       terminate the process with a core dump.

       SIGPWR (which is not specified in POSIX.1-2001) is typically ignored by
       default on those other UNIX systems where it appears.

       SIGIO (which is not specified in POSIX.1-2001) is ignored by default on
       several other UNIX systems.

   Queueing and delivery semantics for standard signals
       If multiple standard signals are pending for a process, the order in
       which the signals are delivered is unspecified.

       Standard signals do not queue.  If multiple instances of a standard
       signal are generated while that signal is blocked, then only one
       instance of the signal is marked as pending (and the signal will be
       delivered just once when it is unblocked).  In the case where a
       standard signal is already pending, the siginfo_t structure (see
       sigaction(2)) associated with that signal is not overwritten on arrival
       of subsequent instances of the same signal.  Thus, the process will
       receive the information associated with the first instance of the
       signal.

   Signal numbering for standard signals
       The numeric value for each signal is given in the table below.  As
</pre>

       shows the signal number on x86, ARM, and most other architectures; the
       second value is for Alpha and SPARC; the third is for MIPS; and the
       last is for PARISC.  A dash (-) denotes that a signal is absent on the
       corresponding architecture.

       Signal        x86/ARM     Alpha/   MIPS   PARISC   Notes
                   most others   SPARC
       ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
       SIGHUP           1           1       1       1

       SIGQUIT          3           3       3       3

       SIGBUS           7          10      10      10
       SIGEMT           -           7       7      -
       SIGFPE           8           8       8       8
       SIGKILL          9           9       9       9
       SIGUSR1         10          30      16      16
       SIGSEGV         11          11      11      11
       SIGUSR2         12          31      17      17
       SIGPIPE         13          13      13      13
       SIGALRM         14          14      14      14
       SIGTERM         15          15      15      15
       SIGSTKFLT       16          -       -        7
       SIGCHLD         17          20      18      18
       SIGCLD           -          -       18      -
       SIGCONT         18          19      25      26
       SIGSTOP         19          17      23      24
       SIGTSTP         20          18      24      25
       SIGTTIN         21          21      26      27
       SIGTTOU         22          22      27      28
       SIGURG          23          16      21      29

       SIGXFSZ         25          25      31      30
       SIGVTALRM       26          26      28      20
